WEBVTT

00:03.138 --> 00:06.422
Welcome to the Life Church Podcast.

00:06.442 --> 00:11.568
We are in Acts 2 4 to 2 community, a family on a mission to bring a life of Jesus to warranty.

00:13.130 --> 00:20.940
We hope you're ready to hear what God has to say to you today through His Word and by His Spirit.

00:20.960 --> 00:21.801
I'll do my best.

00:22.562 --> 00:32.434
And the passage that we've been, essentially we've been given when we've prepared is Romans chapter 5 verse 8, and it says this, but God demonstrates His own love for us in this.

00:32.514 --> 00:35.097
While we were still sinners, Christ died for us.

00:35.777 --> 00:41.644
It's a very short verse in terms of words, but it's also an utterly profound truth that I'm going to try and unpack.

00:42.164 --> 00:45.908
And I'm going to start by splitting these verses down and delving into each one.

00:47.029 --> 00:50.793
So the first one, but God demonstrates his own love for us in this.

00:51.574 --> 00:56.299
So I want to start by defining God's love and how it is expressed.

00:56.820 --> 00:59.122
So in English, we have only one word for love.

00:59.330 --> 01:00.752
but it can have many different meanings.

01:01.212 --> 01:05.937
So we can love our husbands or wives, we can love sports, we can love a cheeky nandos.

01:06.538 --> 01:09.201
We know what we mean when we use that one word in English.

01:09.981 --> 01:12.624
In Greek, which is a language the New Testament is written in.

01:13.605 --> 01:19.492
There's not only one word for love, there's in fact four, all separate and different, each with their own distinct meanings.

01:19.872 --> 01:24.497
I'm just gonna apply those meanings to my own life just to show the difference between them.

01:25.198 --> 01:29.202
So you have the four here, so you have

01:29.314 --> 01:31.177
Eros, which is romantic love.

01:31.277 --> 01:33.200
That's the way in which I love my wife.

01:33.901 --> 01:34.722
Have Storgay.

01:35.023 --> 01:36.885
That's affectionate or familiar love.

01:37.166 --> 01:40.070
I've got two nephews and a niece who I have great affection for.

01:40.851 --> 01:41.232
Felia.

01:41.452 --> 01:42.975
Now, this is a love between friends.

01:43.335 --> 01:47.682
I'm impressed to have blessed to have some very close friendships with people, some of whom are here.

01:48.343 --> 01:49.064
And Agape.

01:49.485 --> 01:51.928
Now, this is the love that Paul's talking about in this passage.

01:52.549 --> 01:58.418
And this is the supreme self-giving, self-sacrificing love that puts others above itself.

01:59.458 --> 02:03.404
Now, culture and society often speaks about love in many different ways.

02:03.464 --> 02:06.188
You have poems, plays, books, songs, films.

02:06.829 --> 02:15.101
Now, if you had to pick one of these four types of love, which one do we think our society and culture focuses on the most?

02:15.882 --> 02:20.488
Which form is held up as the highest and best expression of love?

02:20.508 --> 02:21.650
So I would say Eros.

02:22.562 --> 02:23.644
So romantic love.

02:23.744 --> 02:25.748
It's the form of love that everyone talks about.

02:25.988 --> 02:28.133
It's the form of love no one wants to miss out on.

02:28.694 --> 02:34.104
It's the form of love that we can feel as though if we aren't experiencing it, then we aren't really experiencing love.

02:35.567 --> 02:39.033
Is romantic love is eros, the highest form of love imaginable?

02:39.915 --> 02:41.017
Our culture says yes.

02:41.738 --> 02:42.580
Jesus says no.

02:44.002 --> 02:45.906
If you read in John chapter 15,

02:46.082 --> 02:51.069
Verses 12 to 13, it says this, my command is this, this is Jesus speaking to his disciples.

02:51.649 --> 02:54.593
Love and none, love each other as I have loved you.

02:55.234 --> 02:57.057
Greater love has no one than this.

02:57.097 --> 02:59.640
To get married, how are they?

02:59.660 --> 02:59.840
No.

03:00.421 --> 03:02.304
Says this, greater love has no one than this.

03:02.664 --> 03:04.947
To lay down one's life for one's friends.

03:06.569 --> 03:09.313
Greater love has no one than this to lay down your life.

03:10.355 --> 03:12.978
Jesus doesn't say there's no greater love than getting married.

03:13.570 --> 03:21.981
According to Jesus, the greatest form of love is laying down your life self-sacrificially for others as he demonstrates not long after he speaks this to his disciples.

03:22.562 --> 03:23.884
That's true agape love.

03:24.425 --> 03:26.087
That's the highest form of love.

03:26.868 --> 03:34.418
Agape is so much greater than the other three, so much so that when you apply agape love to the other three, it enhances all of them.

03:35.490 --> 03:40.737
So if you love sacrificially in romantic relationships, you'll have better marriages and relationships.

03:40.758 --> 03:45.184
If you love sacrificially within your family and towards your children, you'll have stronger bonds with them.

03:45.925 --> 03:50.672
If you love your friends sacrificially, you'll have richer and more meaningful relationships and friendships.

03:51.232 --> 03:56.139
So when this verse talks about God demonstrating his love, the love we're talking about is agape.

03:57.161 --> 04:03.570
So I recently listened to a podcast where there was an exchange between a Christian bishop

04:04.450 --> 04:12.434
and an atheist who was hosting this podcast and they were discussing partway through about love and how we explain the nature of it.

04:14.460 --> 04:19.154
And the atheist was trying to explain love in purely biological and materialistic terms.

04:19.586 --> 04:22.351
Purpose is leaving no room for any kind of divine input.

04:22.371 --> 04:35.292
The whole point of his saying was that you can explain, you don't need divine love, you can explain it a way it can be chemical, it can be biological, it's just things in our heads, there's nothing special or there's no higher plane regarding it.

04:36.033 --> 04:43.986
So for example, we only love our partners and our children because our job as organisms on this planet is to propagate our genes, just like animals.

04:44.098 --> 04:50.729
So we only really want to love and protect them so that our genetic material has the chance to pass on down the generations and thrive.

04:56.579 --> 05:02.149
When it comes to loving other friends or neighbours or the members of the family, well, that's simply self-interest, he said.

05:02.710 --> 05:05.254
As a community, we must all work together to survive.

05:05.635 --> 05:10.002
So having a good reputation among friends is important, so we mutually cooperate.

05:10.306 --> 05:14.091
There were more explanations and I'm not a scientist so I'm not going to go into all of them.

05:14.652 --> 05:24.506
But essentially what this atheist's podcast was saying was that love can be boiled down to a pragmatic survival instinct that protects your ability to pass on your genetic material.

05:24.986 --> 05:25.547
That's the point.

05:25.567 --> 05:26.428
There's nothing greater.

05:26.448 --> 05:27.290
There's nothing higher.

05:27.590 --> 05:29.513
It's simply a survival mechanism.

05:31.515 --> 05:36.262
And the bishop listened graciously to these naturalistic explanations of love.

05:36.282 --> 05:39.186
He then told the atheist a story of a Franciscan friar

05:39.362 --> 05:43.588
in World War II called Maximilian Kolb, who I have a picture of here.

05:45.050 --> 05:49.697
So during the war, Maximilian was captured by the Nazis for helping to hide Jews.

05:50.157 --> 05:55.725
And he was taken to Auschwitz, which is the notorious Nazi death camp, where he served as a priest helping others.

05:56.526 --> 06:00.592
And while he was at Auschwitz in August 1941, a prisoner escaped from the camp.

06:01.413 --> 06:07.442
In retaliation for this escape, the camp commandant selected 10 men from the camp at random.

06:07.970 --> 06:13.316
These 10 men were to be executed by being put on an underground bunker and left there till they starved to death.

06:14.317 --> 06:20.723
Maximilian was present when this happened, but he was not one of the 10 men chosen, and he didn't know any of them who they were.

06:20.763 --> 06:22.145
They were all strangers to him.

06:23.346 --> 06:28.171
And as the men began to be dragged away to their deaths, one man cried out that he had a wife and a child.

06:29.312 --> 06:34.578
Maximilian calmly stepped forward and asked the commandant if he could take this man's place instead.

06:35.330 --> 06:39.196
He didn't know the man, he had no connection with him whatsoever.

06:39.216 --> 06:42.923
The common dance agreed and Maximilian was taken to his death.

06:44.004 --> 06:53.781
And after the bishop had finished this story, with the atheist podcast that it is very best to try and explain why anybody might do this in purely naturalistic terms.

06:54.562 --> 07:01.714
It flew in the face of everything he had previously said about why love is essentially purely a selfish biological process.

07:02.178 --> 07:09.388
It perhaps shouldn't come as a surprise to us that an atheist would struggle to explain what might motivate this kind of divine agape love.

07:09.989 --> 07:11.371
And essentially, Trizy might.

07:11.391 --> 07:15.276
He had no answer because that kind of love is divine.

07:15.316 --> 07:16.899
It's not naturalistic.

07:16.999 --> 07:18.140
It's not chemicals in your head.

07:18.721 --> 07:21.825
And that kind of example proved it very, very well.

07:23.808 --> 07:27.954
So this is the same kind of love that God demonstrates to us in action, not words.

07:28.130 --> 07:31.534
Jesus sets this standard of divine love for His disciples.

07:32.095 --> 07:36.721
He then immediately goes on to demonstrate it to them by dying on the cross in their place.

07:37.441 --> 07:40.585
He perfectly demonstrates self-giving sacrificial love.

07:41.707 --> 07:45.832
God demonstrates His love for us by making a way for us to be in relationship with Him.

07:46.593 --> 07:54.683
God so desires relationship with us, He was willing to endure His Son being murdered by sinners so those same sinners could come to Him.

07:55.704 --> 07:57.426
Without this demonstration of love,

07:57.634 --> 08:00.198
It would be impossible for any of us to come to Jesus.

08:01.581 --> 08:03.144
I'll expand on this on my neck points.

08:03.404 --> 08:06.449
The second point is this, while we were yet sinners.

08:07.271 --> 08:07.471
Okay.

08:08.433 --> 08:10.757
So what is a sinner?

08:13.181 --> 08:21.356
So upon here, so a sinner is essentially in the Greek, it is about, it's a word that means missing the mark.

08:22.337 --> 08:22.738
Okay.

08:23.170 --> 08:30.902
So essentially what it means is it's either someone who's broken a religious or moral law, or someone who has missed the mark.

08:35.069 --> 08:43.603
So in Jesus' day, essentially what would happen was that you're expected to kind of separate yourself from sinners.

08:43.663 --> 08:45.746
You would be made unclean by them.

08:45.858 --> 08:51.206
We've got a very short story about this, which is regarding a friend of mine, he's a good friend of mine.

08:52.067 --> 08:57.736
Many years ago at Lifechurch, I invited some people out to a pub to hang out, just for fun.

08:58.878 --> 09:01.342
I didn't invite my friend, though we're very close.

09:01.362 --> 09:04.507
I can't remember why, but it's nothing, not because I'd fallen out.

09:04.927 --> 09:06.149
I'd just forgotten to invite him.

09:06.970 --> 09:14.642
Turned out that my friend on that same night had gone out with his wife and his parents-in-law, and they happened to come to the very same place that we were

09:15.042 --> 09:15.863
slightly awkward.

09:16.364 --> 09:20.329
So when we walked in, like, oh, hello, you know, et cetera, had a bit of a laugh about it.

09:20.850 --> 09:23.132
But my friend was actually slightly a little bit bothered.

09:23.333 --> 09:24.134
We were still friends.

09:24.174 --> 09:24.594
It's fine.

09:25.275 --> 09:26.717
And he's on the way home and the car.

09:26.737 --> 09:27.598
And he's talking to his wife.

09:27.638 --> 09:28.960
And she's like, just, it's nothing.

09:28.980 --> 09:29.841
They just let it go.

09:29.901 --> 09:30.342
It's fine.

09:30.362 --> 09:31.223
Doesn't mean anything.

09:31.243 --> 09:32.605
You've been friends for ages.

09:33.506 --> 09:35.028
My friend couldn't shake this idea.

09:35.488 --> 09:37.191
And he went to sleep still thinking about it.

09:37.271 --> 09:38.893
And he had a dream about it.

09:39.393 --> 09:41.076
And my friend has very vivid dreams.

09:42.518 --> 09:42.898
And

09:43.170 --> 09:48.758
During this dream, he was in church with me, and he was trying to get me to explain, why had I not invited him?

09:48.778 --> 09:49.940
Why had I not brought him along?

09:51.262 --> 09:55.368
And I apparently looked at him very seriously in this dream and said, do you really want to know why?

09:56.430 --> 09:57.211
I said, yeah, I do.

09:57.732 --> 10:04.261
And apparently in the dream, because I would never say this in real life, I walked towards him, put my face in his and said, because you're a sinner.

10:06.545 --> 10:12.914
That is not who I am, but that is what happened in the dream.

10:13.218 --> 10:17.624
So, but it's kind of, that was the attitude of the day.

10:17.804 --> 10:22.571
So if you're a sinner, you're over here, I'm over here, you're unclean, you're unholy.

10:22.912 --> 10:25.776
I don't want to take myself by association with you.

10:25.796 --> 10:26.937
I'm going to stay over here.

10:27.318 --> 10:30.362
That's exactly what the Pharisees and religious leaders did.

10:30.402 --> 10:34.187
That's not what Jesus does.

10:34.868 --> 10:38.834
And he tells us why in Matthew chapter 9, verses 12 to 13,

10:39.362 --> 10:47.073
So when the teachers of the law who were Pharisees saw a meeting with the sinners and tax collectors, they asked his disciples, why does he eat with tax collectors and sinners?

10:48.034 --> 10:52.220
On hearing this, Jesus said to them, it is not the healthy who need a doctor, but the sick.

10:53.121 --> 10:55.845
I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners.

10:56.866 --> 11:02.674
Now you know if you read any of the gospels that when Jesus was teaching throughout his ministry, throughout those three years,

11:02.946 --> 11:10.276
He was constantly correcting the faulty interpretations and incorrect teachings of the day, usually the ones that the Pharisees themselves held to.

11:11.377 --> 11:16.925
Jesus tells us it's not come to abolish the law but to fulfill it and interpret it correctly.

11:17.305 --> 11:21.892
And the religious and legal experts are always arguing with him about it and trying to catch him out.

11:22.412 --> 11:27.840
They challenge him publicly regularly with questions that weren't sincere but were designed to try and show him up.

11:28.841 --> 11:32.626
And want us to pay attention to this point, looking at the scripture.

11:33.474 --> 11:39.981
Jesus has no problem correcting the religious leaders and the faulty interpretations and he doesn't care how upset they get in the process.

11:40.522 --> 11:44.626
He actually is, they tried to stone him at least twice before he's crucified.

11:45.006 --> 11:47.569
So Jesus is happy to upset people and correct people.

11:47.709 --> 11:48.490
He has no problem.

11:49.411 --> 11:59.442
In the passage we've just read, Jesus corrects the Pharisees faulty understanding of mercy and grace and why he is not tainted by sinners and he will actually go and spend time with them.

11:59.842 --> 12:04.169
But if you notice, there's one assertion made by the Pharisees that he doesn't correct.

12:05.411 --> 12:10.239
Jesus acknowledges the fact that the people he is spending time with are in fact sinners.

12:11.240 --> 12:12.783
He doesn't correct that assertion.

12:12.943 --> 12:14.265
He doesn't say, come on, they're not sinners.

12:14.285 --> 12:15.186
What are you talking about?

12:16.428 --> 12:18.972
He doesn't say, are you awful judgmental Pharisees?

12:19.012 --> 12:19.754
They're not sinners.

12:20.335 --> 12:22.879
How dare you make them feel guilty and judge them in this way?

12:22.919 --> 12:24.301
It's a terrible thing to call them.

12:24.782 --> 12:25.042
No.

12:25.538 --> 12:26.760
He doesn't correct them on that point.

12:27.220 --> 12:30.625
Both the Pharisees and Jesus agree on the fact that these people are sinners.

12:31.126 --> 12:33.328
They are separated from God and they are lost.

12:33.869 --> 12:35.491
Jesus doesn't deny or contest it.

12:35.772 --> 12:37.915
What he corrects is their attitude towards them.

12:38.636 --> 12:43.402
He shows that these are exactly the people God cares about and wants to save from their sin.

12:44.023 --> 12:47.448
In fact, that's exactly why he has come to dwell among us in the first place.

12:47.468 --> 12:52.274
We know from John chapter three that he didn't send his son into the world to condemn it, but to save it.

12:53.058 --> 12:59.786
He's going to the people who the Pharisees turn away from them and criticizing them because they won't engage with the lost.

12:59.806 --> 13:06.133
Jesus knows that the sinners he spends time with are under God's judgment and wrath, but he refuses to leave them there.

13:06.614 --> 13:11.519
He pursues them and loves them and he doesn't care about other people's perception of him while he does it.

13:12.741 --> 13:15.244
One thing I want to look at before I move on to my last point is this.

13:16.145 --> 13:20.690
We've defined what it is to be a sinner and acknowledge that we're guilty of sinning against God.

13:20.802 --> 13:26.310
But the key part of the Scripture is this, while we were sinners, Christ died for us.

13:26.330 --> 13:36.384
While we were still sinners, God hasn't waited for us to get our act together, start behaving ourselves properly, before He acted in supreme sacrificial love towards us.

13:37.065 --> 13:44.435
He demonstrated His love for us while we were still His enemies, while we were still unholy, while we were still opposed to His will.

13:46.018 --> 13:49.042
This is one of the most unique cornerstones of the Christian faith.

13:49.538 --> 13:50.720
loving ones enemies.

13:51.441 --> 13:55.046
Jesus lays out why in Matthew chapter 5 verses 43 to 48.

14:01.394 --> 14:04.879
You have heard that it was said, love your neighbor and hate your enemy.

14:05.500 --> 14:11.628
But I tell you, love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you, that you may be children of your father in heaven.

14:12.469 --> 14:18.738
He causes his son to rise on the evil and the good and sends rain on the righteous and the unrighteous.

14:19.426 --> 14:22.530
If you love those who love you, what reward will you get?

14:23.712 --> 14:25.534
Are not even the tax collectors doing that?

14:26.235 --> 14:29.960
And if you agree only your own people, what are you doing more than others?

14:30.400 --> 14:31.782
Do not even pagans do that.

14:32.363 --> 14:35.687
Be perfect therefore, as your heavenly father is perfect.

14:36.949 --> 14:43.718
Okay, so I think sometimes we don't realize what an incredible teaching that is.

14:44.279 --> 14:46.802
We kind of, if you brought up in church, like I was,

14:46.882 --> 14:49.204
You sort of go, oh yes, we love our enemies, it's very hard.

14:49.284 --> 14:51.967
Nothing like this existed before.

14:52.007 --> 14:58.894
This isn't even in the Old Testament that Jesus actually corrects and says, love your friends, hate your enemies.

14:58.954 --> 14:59.915
That's what you do.

15:00.836 --> 15:06.161
For Jesus to essentially turn that around is so radical, you'd struggle to get your head around it.

15:06.742 --> 15:14.610
And what he teaches is there's merit before God in loving people who hate you, who oppose you, who persecute you.

15:15.106 --> 15:18.490
It's genius because what he says is, well, think about it.

15:18.611 --> 15:24.238
Even the worst kinds of sinners and unbelievers are capable of loving people who love them back.

15:25.860 --> 15:31.868
He says, if you really want to express perfect agape love like your father, then practice loving your enemies.

15:32.348 --> 15:32.649
Okay.

15:32.669 --> 15:33.610
Well, why?

15:34.591 --> 15:36.594
Because that's how God reaches us.

15:37.090 --> 15:38.872
And it's how he wants us to reach others.

15:39.433 --> 15:50.364
Says in Romans chapter two that God's kindness is designed to lead us towards repentance, that we should be so moved by God's mercy and grace towards us that we want to follow and please him.

15:51.105 --> 15:56.711
The love and grace of God is demonstrated to us first, precisely when we don't deserve it.

15:57.973 --> 16:03.058
Jesus says to let you light shine before others that they may see your good deeds and glorify God.

16:03.266 --> 16:09.252
Our actions in loving our enemies, just how God loved us when we were His enemies, draws people.

16:10.012 --> 16:12.675
It's crazy and it's radical and it's attractive.

16:15.598 --> 16:24.687
While we were sinners, breakers of the law, enemies of God with no defense for our sin, Jesus chose to demonstrate His perfect love for us by dying on the cross.

16:26.268 --> 16:32.434
And the third point here, Christ died for us.

16:32.770 --> 16:35.413
I'm gonna sort of raise a question, which is this.

16:35.914 --> 16:37.356
What did Jesus need to die for?

16:38.257 --> 16:39.298
And why did he need to die?

16:40.179 --> 16:45.145
Sometimes a controversial question, it can sometimes be a controversial question even in Christian circles.

16:45.906 --> 16:52.354
And a frequent criticism of those who don't believe in God is to say, well, why can't God just decide to forgive?

16:53.255 --> 16:54.717
Okay, God is love after all.

16:55.358 --> 17:02.066
Why can't he simply overlook our sin if he wants so badly to be in relationship with us and the sin is what's in the way?

17:02.306 --> 17:05.130
Why can't he just ignore that and look past it?

17:05.971 --> 17:07.513
He's God, he's all powerful.

17:08.314 --> 17:11.598
Why does he have to go through his whole plan of Jesus dying on a cross?

17:12.279 --> 17:16.384
Surely God can think of a better way than to have to sacrifice his own son.

17:17.185 --> 17:20.429
Why doesn't God just snap his fingers and forgive us and save us?

17:21.871 --> 17:23.994
And the problem, if you can call it a problem, is this.

17:29.141 --> 17:30.162
God is bound

17:30.594 --> 17:34.498
by his very nature and character to punish sin and wickedness.

17:35.319 --> 17:39.544
He must do so, otherwise he's not a good or just God.

17:40.625 --> 17:52.599
There's a quote from Harvard theologian, I'm gonna read, he's called Miraslav Volf, and he described himself as someone who used to struggle with the idea of God's wrath against humans for their sin.

17:53.560 --> 17:58.866
If God was love, he reasoned, surely he couldn't be angry and wrathful as well, that's a contradiction.

18:00.514 --> 18:08.902
And he continued to struggle with this tension until he closely witnessed such evil and wickedness that it changed his mind.

18:09.503 --> 18:10.544
I'm going to read a quote from him.

18:10.604 --> 18:13.426
It's from his book and the book is called Free of Charge.

18:15.088 --> 18:19.372
And he says this, I used to think that wrath was unworthy of God.

18:20.113 --> 18:20.913
Isn't God love?

18:21.634 --> 18:23.876
Shouldn't divine love be beyond wrath?

18:24.657 --> 18:27.840
God is love and God loves every person and every creature.

18:28.641 --> 18:29.842
That's exactly

18:30.114 --> 18:32.077
why God is wrathful against some of them.

18:32.918 --> 18:39.990
My last resistance to the idea of God's wrath was a casualty of the war in the former Yugoslavia, the region from which I come.

18:40.851 --> 18:46.480
According to some estimates, 200,000 people were killed and over 3 million were displaced.

18:46.500 --> 18:48.423
My villages and cities were destroyed.

18:48.824 --> 18:51.308
My people shelled day in and day out.

18:51.808 --> 18:53.952
Some of them brutalized beyond imagination.

18:54.833 --> 18:57.938
And I could not imagine God not being angry.

18:58.626 --> 19:05.155
Well, think of Rwanda in the last decade of the past century, where 800,000 people were hacked to death in 100 days.

19:05.835 --> 19:07.578
How did God react to the carnage?

19:08.399 --> 19:17.731
By doting on the perpetrators in a grandparently fashion, by refusing to condemn the bloodbath, but instead affirming the perpetrators basic goodness.

19:18.672 --> 19:20.575
Wasn't God fiercely angry with them?

19:21.436 --> 19:26.002
Though I used to complain about the indecency of the idea of God's wrath.

19:26.690 --> 19:33.600
I came to think that I would have to rebel against a God who wasn't wrathful at the sight of the world's evil.

19:34.502 --> 19:36.565
God isn't wrathful in spite of being love.

19:37.346 --> 19:39.449
God is wrathful because God is love.

19:43.515 --> 19:53.490
I believe there's one person who really understood what God's wrath against sin and his grace and love for sinners meant.

19:55.810 --> 20:00.695
And I think this person knew and experienced this better than anyone ever has or ever will.

20:01.275 --> 20:02.136
That's my opinion.

20:02.196 --> 20:06.340
That's not a statement of fact, but I do think that's the case and I'll explain why.

20:07.762 --> 20:09.944
This person is not a great academic theologian.

20:10.565 --> 20:11.826
They're not a famous thinker.

20:11.906 --> 20:13.207
They're not a hero of the faith.

20:14.428 --> 20:15.790
In fact, we don't even know the name.

20:16.831 --> 20:20.595
So I'm going to read from Luke chapter 23 verses 39 to 42.

20:22.737 --> 20:24.018
And this is the scene.

20:24.482 --> 20:25.965
of Jesus's crucifixion.

20:34.159 --> 20:37.605
Jesus has been crucified alongside two of the convicted criminals.

20:37.625 --> 20:39.047
You're probably familiar with the story.

20:39.568 --> 20:40.690
One on either side of him.

20:41.570 --> 20:46.997
And people are mocking Jesus, telling him to bring himself down from the cross if he really is God.

20:47.017 --> 20:53.966
So you have the religious leaders and the stood off at a distance and they're growing and gloating and mocking and saying, well, you know, you performed all this miracles.

20:53.986 --> 20:54.727
You're the Messiah.

20:54.747 --> 20:55.027
Come on.

20:55.287 --> 20:56.088
Let's see something.

20:58.271 --> 21:02.456
It says this, one of the criminals who hung there hurled insults at him.

21:02.917 --> 21:03.858
Aren't you the Messiah?

21:04.299 --> 21:05.680
Save yourself and us.

21:06.642 --> 21:08.063
But the other criminal rebuked him.

21:08.504 --> 21:09.525
Don't you fear God?

21:09.745 --> 21:10.226
He said.

21:10.306 --> 21:14.433
Since you were under the same sentence, we are punished justly.

21:15.155 --> 21:19.061
We are getting what our deeds deserve, but this man has done nothing wrong.

21:20.003 --> 21:23.389
Then he said, Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom.

21:24.311 --> 21:29.119
Jesus answered him, truly, I tell you, today you will be with me in paradise.

21:29.440 --> 21:31.904
There's three things I want to take from this.

21:32.926 --> 21:35.250
First one is recognition.

21:35.714 --> 21:42.581
This is what he says, we are punished justly for we are getting what our deeds deserve, but this man has done nothing wrong.

21:43.622 --> 21:45.644
There's no argument from the second thief.

21:46.305 --> 21:47.306
There's no excuses.

21:47.666 --> 21:48.827
There's only an acknowledgement.

21:48.887 --> 21:50.228
He doesn't have a leg to stand on.

21:52.110 --> 21:53.572
We can say we're a good person.

21:53.632 --> 21:54.573
We're not that bad.

21:55.033 --> 21:58.096
We can get angry with God because we don't like his judgment.

21:58.116 --> 22:03.762
But the fact remains, as it says in Romans and as we read last week, that

22:04.578 --> 22:09.045
we are separated from God and deserving of punishment no matter how we might feel about it.

22:10.047 --> 22:12.530
The thief recognizes that Jesus is innocent.

22:13.191 --> 22:16.877
He recognizes he may deserve this punishment, but Jesus does not.

22:29.016 --> 22:29.858
Realization.

22:31.620 --> 22:32.722
So one criminal,

22:33.474 --> 22:36.137
The first one wants something from Jesus.

22:36.838 --> 22:38.581
He acts like Jesus owes him something.

22:38.601 --> 22:43.087
What he's saying is like the religious leader saying, come on, get me off this cross, do something.

22:43.527 --> 22:47.492
If you're God, you need to do what I want now, okay?

22:48.253 --> 22:52.659
The other criminal rebukes him and says, don't you fear God since you're under the same sentence?

22:53.520 --> 22:54.441
He's like, seriously?

22:54.902 --> 22:57.806
Don't you have any humility given your current situation?

22:58.527 --> 23:01.170
Don't act like this Jesus owes us anything.

23:01.794 --> 23:06.799
The second thief realizes it's foolish to demand things of God that you have no right to ask for.

23:07.921 --> 23:10.223
God doesn't owe us anything, okay?

23:10.524 --> 23:19.493
Now we don't mean by that there aren't promises of God that he gives to us out of faithfulness, but what I mean is everything that we receive from God, we don't earn it.

23:20.114 --> 23:22.557
We can't demand it, we're not owed it, okay?

23:24.319 --> 23:26.541
God doesn't owe us anything whether we're Christian or not.

23:27.062 --> 23:31.026
Everything we receive from God is a good gift because of his generosity.

23:31.170 --> 23:33.894
It's one of the criticisms I have.

23:33.975 --> 23:45.453
I'm not going to get too much into this of prosperity theology, which is the health, wealth and prosperity that essentially means that you give a certain amount of money or you give this and then God will give something back.

23:45.493 --> 23:48.899
Essentially treats God like a cosmic slot machine, which is why I don't like it.

23:49.399 --> 23:56.050
But one of the things that I really don't like about it is that there's a hint that God owes us something.

23:56.610 --> 23:58.193
There's a hint that, well, we give something here.

23:58.213 --> 24:01.438
Well, God sort of has to give us something back, doesn't he?

24:01.838 --> 24:04.643
You know, God, he kind of owes us something.

24:04.703 --> 24:09.310
If you're giving this really, you know, it's almost like, well, God has to give us something back.

24:09.330 --> 24:11.534
Whether we deserve it or not, it's about the fact we don't.

24:12.315 --> 24:17.163
Like I said, cosmic slot machine, we put stuff in and God gives us stuff back and that is not how it works.

24:19.026 --> 24:23.954
I often wake up in the morning and get a strong instruction from the Holy Spirit to thank God.

24:24.610 --> 24:26.754
I give him thanks that I'm waking up in a worn bed.

24:27.875 --> 24:30.981
I can go downstairs and get food and drink that isn't scarce.

24:31.902 --> 24:33.465
I'm married, I have a job.

24:34.346 --> 24:36.991
All of these things are gifts from God that I don't deserve.

24:37.151 --> 24:39.795
God doesn't owe me any single thing of that.

24:40.376 --> 24:44.984
He gives them to me because of his generous nature, not because I've done anything to earn it.

24:48.290 --> 24:50.994
The last one here I'm going to look at is reaching.

24:52.098 --> 24:56.303
And the second thief says, Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom.

24:58.145 --> 25:01.168
And the thief says to Jesus, your kingdom, did you notice that?

25:01.809 --> 25:02.530
Your kingdom.

25:03.571 --> 25:09.718
What that says to me is this thief, the second thief, doesn't expect to be going where Jesus is going.

25:12.061 --> 25:15.845
He thinks that Jesus' kingdom is not for a man like him to enter.

25:17.267 --> 25:20.370
Do you remember what the first thief said when he wanted something from Jesus?

25:20.514 --> 25:22.937
He demanded to be taken with Jesus.

25:24.940 --> 25:28.105
He said, come with me, get yourself off this cross and take me with you.

25:28.145 --> 25:29.307
Come on, do something.

25:31.690 --> 25:33.633
What does the second thief ask Jesus to do?

25:35.095 --> 25:35.836
Just remember me.

25:37.498 --> 25:41.985
The second thief says, I know you're going into your kingdom, your kingdom.

25:42.726 --> 25:46.532
I know I've no right to ask you to take me with you because I don't deserve it.

25:47.192 --> 25:48.274
Just please remember me.

25:49.282 --> 25:55.831
And the most beautiful reply, this thief in agony and close to death could ever have heard comes back to his ears.

25:56.692 --> 26:00.797
Jesus answered him, truly, I tell you, today you will be with me in paradise.

26:02.359 --> 26:08.267
Jesus says to the second thief, because of the love I'm demonstrating right now, there is a way for you to join me.

26:09.289 --> 26:10.370
I see your humility.

26:11.011 --> 26:13.695
I see your acknowledgement of your sin and failure.

26:14.015 --> 26:19.282
And I see you reaching to me, knowing I only hope with no expectation, no demand.

26:19.522 --> 26:22.566
just to hope that you're generous enough to treat me with grace.

26:24.630 --> 26:26.472
You didn't demand entry into my kingdom.

26:27.173 --> 26:30.959
You expected that you alone would be bearing the consequences of your own sin.

26:32.301 --> 26:33.983
Well, says Jesus, there's good news.

26:35.826 --> 26:37.268
I've paid that penalty for you.

26:38.009 --> 26:38.911
So you're coming with me.

26:43.898 --> 26:46.722
There's one last verse I want to finish with.

26:47.403 --> 26:49.426
It's a verse from a song called Love and Carner

26:50.146 --> 26:55.092
by Stuart Townen, and I think it sums up well what I've spoken about today.

26:56.133 --> 27:05.744
There are eight lines, typically by the fifth or sixth one is when I start choking up, so put your bets in now as to when that will happen.

27:07.045 --> 27:10.309
So he says this, flipping it already.

27:14.274 --> 27:14.614
Is what?

27:17.057 --> 27:17.938
Anybody?

27:18.658 --> 27:22.843
As a sheet before the shearer, you were silent in your pain.

27:25.947 --> 27:31.113
You endured humiliation at the hands of those you'd made.

27:34.197 --> 27:38.623
And as hell unleashed its fury, you were lifted on a tree.

27:40.765 --> 27:42.427
Crying, Father, God, forgive them.

27:43.108 --> 27:44.690
Place their punishment on me.

27:48.706 --> 27:51.431
That's the essence, I hope, of what I've spoken about today.

27:52.352 --> 27:58.082
That while we were still sinners, God demonstrates his love for us, and he died for us to make a way.

28:00.566 --> 28:02.069
We've come to the end of this week's message.

28:02.710 --> 28:04.313
We hope you've been impacted and inspired.

28:05.174 --> 28:11.986
Please keep up to date with everything that's happening by visiting our website at www.livechurch.com.

